  "datePublished": "2025-12-31",
  "description": "¶What this lesson covers What a sign is, how Peirce\u0026rsquo;s triadic model differs from Saussure\u0026rsquo;s dyadic model, the role of the interpretant, and the major classifications of signs.\n¶Prerequisites No formal prerequisites. Familiarity with the idea that words, images, and gestures can \u0026ldquo;stand for\u0026rdquo; things is sufficient.\n¶Two traditions Modern semiotics has two founding lineages, and they disagree on what a sign is. (For their broader intellectual contexts, see Peircean Semiotics and Saussurean Semiology.)\n",
